FROGS 5 WRITING GUIDE
For anyone -- human or AI -- writing prose for any FROGS 5 campaign.
Read this before you write read-aloud text, in-world documents, or NPC dialogue.

The principles and examples in sections I-IV and VI are project-agnostic; use them anywhere.
Section V is one worked example drawn from Torygg's Legacy. Plain text; "--" stands in for an
em-dash. (In Torygg's Legacy these rules are also summarized in AI_README section X.)

=======================================================
I. THE ONE PRINCIPLE: EVERY WORD IS STRUCTURAL
=======================================================

Maximum detail, minimum words. These do not conflict, because detail is information and
filler is length wearing information's clothes.

A word earns its place by changing the meaning of the sentence. The test is the cut: remove
the word, and if the meaning holds, the word was doing no work -- leave it cut. Filler is not
neutral. It buries the picture it claims to paint and inflates length with nothing.

Each sentence builds on the one before it. The reader is assembling a mental model as they
go; every sentence either adds to that model or muddies it. You earn a subversion only by
first constructing the thing you subvert.

Everything in sections II-V follows from this principle. They are the specific ways prose
breaks it.

=======================================================
II. THE HARD BANS
=======================================================

--- 1. NEVER WRITE A PLAYER CHARACTER'S ACTIONS, CHOICES, OR REALIZATIONS ---

Discovery belongs to the players at the table. Prep that makes a PC solve, read, deduce, or
speak a discovery steals the reveal and the agency, and it feels terrible to the player whose
character was just driven without them. We are capable writers; we never need this crutch.

Write what is PRESENT (the object, the text, the evidence). Put what it MEANS in a separate
GM-only block. Hand the players the thing; let them drive. A PC's expertise is an opening the
GM offers live -- never a conclusion prep dictates.

  BEFORE: She picks the lock, steps inside, and realizes the place was abandoned in a hurry.
  AFTER:  The lock gives on the second pin. Inside, two drawers hang open and a chair lies on
          its side; a half-packed satchel sits on the bed. [GM-only: someone left in a hurry.
          Let the players read the room and say so; do not say it for them.]

--- 2. "COLD" IS BANNED AS TEXTURE; SO ARE MOOD-WORDS USED AS FILLER ---

"Cold" gets pasted onto everything -- the lid, the fire, the hate, the love. When everything
is cold, the word means nothing and does no descriptive work. Watch the same way for "wrong,"
"ancient," "eerie," "dread," "a presence," "an absence," "something radiates/pulses." These
name a mood instead of building one.

And the damage outlasts the sentence. A texture word is read as fact and recorded as canon;
later beats must then honor it or fight it. A "cold" dropped in for atmosphere becomes a
constraint the next writer trips over -- a contradiction manufactured out of a word that was
describing nothing. Filler is not inert. It hardens into false canon and costs you downstream.

Earn the mood with one concrete, physical, specific detail.

  BEFORE: The table is wrong somehow. A cold dread hangs over the cold remains of a meal.
  AFTER:  Four chairs are pushed back from the table, and the bread on the plates has gone
          green and hard.

--- 3. DESCRIBE WHAT IS THERE; NEVER DESCRIBE BY WHAT ISN'T ---

Subtractive negation injects context into the reader's model and then makes them delete it a
breath later -- errant detail raised only to be discarded. It guarantees confusion and burns
the reader's attention for nothing.

State the positive fact.

  BEFORE: The door wasn't forced. It was opened from the inside. No marks, no damage.
  AFTER:  The door stands open, the bar lifted clear and leaned against the wall beside it.

(There is one legitimate use of negation -- see section III.)

--- 4. DO NOT INVENT CONNECTIONS THE STRUCTURE DOESN'T SUPPORT ---

When two factions, threats, or plot threads are established as separate, do not link, contrast,
or echo them to manufacture resonance. A character should not "brace" for one enemy inside
another's content. Invented cross-connections break established canon and confuse players who
are tracking those threads as distinct. If a connection is not already in the structure, it
does not exist. (E.g., in Torygg's Legacy the Dragon Cult and the Dagon corruption are
separate enemies -- never tie them together.)

--- 5. NO OMNISCIENCE; DESCRIBE IN THE ORDER THINGS ARE PERCEIVED ---

Writers reflexively hand characters and readers knowledge no one present could have -- duration,
history, an actor's intent, the meaning of a thing rather than its appearance. They also
describe out of sequence, reaching back to narrate a moment already passed. Both yank the
reader off their feet.

Only what is observable right now belongs in the read-aloud. Conclusions about history or
intent belong in the GM-only note, drawn by the players if at all. And describe events in the
order the characters meet them: if the text is read once the party is inside a room, do not
narrate what they felt on the way in.

  BEFORE: The heat hits you before you reach the door. The lamps have burned untended for a
          century, and you know at once the owner left in no hurry.
  AFTER:  The room is warm. The lamps burn straight and even. [GM-only: they have burned
          untended for a century and the owner left unhurried -- let the players infer the
          calm from the order of the place; state neither outright.]

(Related: voice is a TELL. Keep an in-world document true to its writer; a private log should
never explain things to an outsider for the reader's benefit.)

=======================================================
III. THE ONE LEGITIMATE NEGATION: ADDITIVE, NOT SUBTRACTIVE
=======================================================

"Not just X -- Y" works only when X is true, STAYS true, and Y stacks a deeper layer on top
of it. The reader keeps both.

  GOOD: "Not just filler, it is structural waste." Filler is real; waste is the truth built
        above it. Both words do work, and the sentence escalates. This CONSTRUCTS the thing.

The banned version asserts X only to erase it ("not cold, but ..."). That is destruction:
it builds an understanding and then demands the reader tear it down.

THE TEST: does the negated clause survive as true and get built on? Keep it. Is it raised
only to be knocked down? Cut it and state the real thing alone. Most negation fails this
test; default to stating Y by itself.

=======================================================
IV. CALIBRATION (the GM's stated preferences)
=======================================================

- READ-ALOUD AND IN-WORLD DOCS carry the strict standard. Mechanical text (stat blocks, GM
  directions) may stay terse shorthand, held to clarity rather than cadence.
- GM READ-OUTS STAY. Keep the read-aloud clean; put interpretation in a separate GM-only
  block ("What this establishes"). The GM wants the facts fast and the prose uncluttered.
- EARNED LYRICISM IS WELCOME. Figurative language and longer cadence are good wherever each
  one carries something a plain sentence cannot. The economy rule still governs: a simile
  that decorates is filler; a simile that conveys is structure.
- EMOTION: lead with the concrete fact, then add a short GM-only cue for the intended feeling
  and delivery. Show the evidence first; the one-line tone note rides underneath it.

=======================================================
V. WORKED EXAMPLE: AN EMPTY THRONE (from Torygg's Legacy)
=======================================================

The party reaches the chamber a powerful enemy woke in and walked out of. He is gone; they
read him off what he left. The goal is to make them feel his strength, his patience, and his
intent -- through present, observable evidence, with no one in the room.

THE BEFORE (breaks rules 2, 3, and 5):
  "The lid is thrown aside -- not lifted, THROWN, cracked against the dais by something that
   did not need leverage. The cold here is not the ward's clean absence. It is the cold of
   something that lay in the dark hating, with perfect patience, for four thousand years. The
   braziers have stayed lit, and the heat reaches you before the doorway does. A line of
   footprints crosses to the door -- the walk of a man crossing a room he owns -- and you are
   certain that whatever rose from this box already knows you came."

What's wrong:
  - Rule 2: "cold" three times, carrying nothing; "hating" names a mood the prose never shows.
  - Rule 3: "not lifted, THROWN," "did not need leverage," "not the ward's clean absence" all
    describe by negation.
  - Rule 5: "have stayed lit" (how do they know the duration?), "four thousand years" (same),
    "the walk of a man crossing a room he owns" (an inference no one could read off footprints),
    "already knows you came" (flat omniscience). "The heat reaches you before the doorway" is
    out of sequence -- this is read once they are inside.

THE AFTER (shows the same three things through what the eye reports, in order):
  "The room is warm -- warm the way a forge stays warm hours after the smith has gone home.
   The braziers burn straight and white over a floor swept clean. The sarcophagus stands open
   at the center, its lid leaned against the dais: a slab of stone two hands thick, split
   across the middle. A handprint is sunk into the underside, the fingers driven to the second
   knuckle, the stone dimpled around them as though it had gone soft as tallow under the hand.
   The dust inside the box holds a shape -- tall, on its back, arms folded, a mask over the
   face, whole to the shoulders and broken there, where it sat up. From the foot of the dais a
   line of footprints crosses the swept floor to the door, evenly spaced, each stride the
   length of the last."
  WHAT THIS ESTABLISHES (GM-only, for the GM to hold and the players to earn):
  - The warmth, the lit braziers, the swept floor: the chamber is kept and recently used.
  - The handprint on the lid's underside, fingers to the second knuckle: it pushed the lid off
    from inside with one hand, hard enough to dent stone. Strength past mortal scale.
  - The undisturbed dust holding a whole body: it lay still for an age, then rose.
  - The even, unhurried, evenly-spaced footprints to the door: it left at a walk, in no hurry,
    with somewhere to be -- the bearing of something that owns the room.
  - Deliver quiet. This is the first room a true villain occupied; the party becomes people it
    will remember. Lead with the warmth and the handprint.

Why the AFTER works: every claim is something a person standing in the room can see -- the
warmth, the print, the dust, the spacing of the prints. The conclusions the BEFORE stated
outright (strength, patience, ownership, "he knows you came") moved into the GM-only note,
where the players reach them or do not. It runs in order, all in the room, with no reach back
to the approach. The forge simile stays because it carries a fact a plain word would miss --
heat lingering from a source now gone; its old trailing clause ("the heat still pushing off
the walls") was cut, because the simile already said it.

=======================================================
VI. THE SELF-CHECK PASS (run over every draft before it ships)
=======================================================

1. CUT-TEST. Remove each word and clause in turn. If the meaning holds, leave it cut.
2. NEGATION. For every "not X": does X stay true and get built on? If it is raised only to be
   deleted, cut it and state the real thing.
3. PC AGENCY. Did I make a player character solve, read, realize, decide, or speak a
   discovery? Convert it to present evidence plus a GM-only note on the meaning.
4. MOOD-WORDS. Search for cold / wrong / ancient / eerie / dread / absence / presence /
   "something." Replace each with a concrete detail or cut it.
5. CONNECTIONS. Did I link two threads the structure keeps separate? Cut it.
6. OMNISCIENCE. Did I state anything the characters present cannot perceive -- duration,
   history, an actor's intent? Move it to the GM-only note. Is the description in the order
   the characters meet it? Reorder to match.
7. SHOW, DON'T INSTRUCT. The read-aloud shows; the feeling and the meaning live in the
   GM-only note beneath it.
8. SPOKEN TEST (section VII.1). In every sentence, does the subject and verb land before any
   qualifying or interrupting clause? If a clause delays the sentence's own grammar to
   manufacture a reveal, reorder it.
9. BREATH TEST (section VII.2). Can every sentence be said aloud in one breath, with no
   mid-clause pause needed to parse it? Split any that can't.
10. PUNCHLINE TEST (section VII.4). Does any line state the conclusion the table should reach
    on their own? Cut it back to the observable fact and let it sit.

(For first-person / journal / in-character writing, also run section VIII:)
11. NO READER (VIII.1). Does any line betray awareness that someone will read the page -- a
    wink, a comment on how a statement lands, a reference to the page itself? Cut it.
12. NO NAMED FEELING (VIII.2). Did I state the writer's emotion, or cap a passage with a
    summary of their own mood? Cut it; let the pace and the detail carry it.
13. FINGERPRINTS (VIII). Scan for the named AI tells: the hedge-then-wry-turn sentence,
    "which either means X or Y," a closing aphorism, fragment-stacks-for-effect, any sentence
    arranged to resolve elegantly. Each one is the writer composing instead of feeling.

=======================================================
VII. SPOKEN DELIVERY -- WRITE FOR THE EAR, NOT THE EYE
=======================================================

Read-aloud text is performed once, live, out loud, by a human looking up from the page at
four other people. That is a different discipline from prose written to be read silently --
and it is the gap that keeps producing bad read-alouds, because "write for a listener" was
previously stated as a goal with no method attached. For an AI writer this matters doubly:
there is no way to hear a draft back and catch what only reveals itself by ear, so the rules
below are deliberately mechanical -- checkable on the page, without an ear, every time.

--- 1. CHRONOLOGICAL SYNTAX, NOT JUST CHRONOLOGICAL CONTENT ---

Section II.5 already bans out-of-order KNOWLEDGE (don't narrate the approach once they're
already inside). This rule is stricter and sits one level down, inside the sentence: don't
delay a sentence's OWN grammatical resolution to manufacture a reveal. Say the subject, then
the verb, then what happens. A reader can scan ahead to resolve a garden-path sentence; a
listener cannot -- the suspense-through-withheld-syntax move that works on a page just
produces confusion spoken cold.

  BEFORE: "Not at you -- just low, a hunting pass, its downdraft slamming the saddle like a
           fist."
  AFTER:  "The dragon dives low over the saddle -- a hunting pass, not at you -- and the
           downdraft slams into the cart like a fist."

--- 2. ONE BREATH, ONE IDEA ---

If a sentence needs a silent pause mid-clause to parse on a first pass, split it. Target: the
GM can read any single sentence in one breath, without backtracking to re-parse it before
finishing it aloud.

--- 3. LIMIT INTERRUPTION ---

One em-dash or parenthetical aside per sentence, maximum. Stacking two or three interruptions
into one sentence is a page-reading device -- the eye can hold the suspended clause and come
back to it. Spoken cold, stacked interruptions just blur into noise.

--- 4. LET THE DETAIL DO THE CONCLUDING -- DON'T NARRATE THE PUNCHLINE ---

This extends Rule II.1 (never write a PC's realization) to world description generally: state
the observable fact and stop. Do not add the authorial "and isn't that telling" beat on top of
it -- that is the GM concluding out loud for the table, not describing a scene.

  BEFORE: "Pack-laden travois lean against the tentpoles; these people came on FOOT, carrying
           all of it."
  AFTER:  "No cart stands among the tents. No horse is picketed nearby. Pack-frames lean
           against every tentpole."

  (the observable absence is stated; the conclusion -- they travel entirely on foot -- is left
  for the table to reach themselves, exactly the present-evidence/GM-only-meaning split II.5
  already establishes)

--- 5. DIALOGUE CARRIES ITS SPEAKER'S ACTUAL STAKES, NOT A GENERIC VOICE ---

A line should come from what THIS character wants in THIS moment -- a merchant's line should
sound like someone trying to make a sale, a soldier's like someone on duty -- not a
pleasant-sounding line that could belong to anyone filling that role. If a line would work
unchanged in a different NPC's mouth in a different scene, it isn't finished.

=======================================================
VIII. FIRST-PERSON VOICE -- JOURNALS, NOTES, AND ANYTHING WRITTEN IN A CHARACTER'S OWN HAND
=======================================================

This is the standard for ANY in-character writing -- a journal, a margin note, a private
log, a letter, a research record. It took many painful passes to arrive at (the Ismara
alchemy notes), so it is written down here to never re-derive from scratch. It is also the
single hardest register for an AI to hit, because the failure mode is not bad prose -- the
failures usually READ well. They just read like the AI, wearing the character. Section II.5
already flags the seed of this ("voice is a TELL; a private log should never explain things
to an outsider for the reader's benefit"). This section is the full method.

THE ONE PRINCIPLE: NO IRONIC DISTANCE. The writer is INSIDE the moment, absorbed in the
thing, not standing outside it arranging the sentence to land. A person writing privately is
feeling and recording, not composing and performing. Every rule below is a way this principle
breaks.

--- 1. PRIVATE MEANS PRIVATE -- THERE IS NO READER ---
A journal has no audience. Cut every trace of awareness that anyone will read the page:
no "wait till they see this," no commentary on how a statement will land ("untoward to say,"
"not that I care"), no reference to the page itself as an object ("this word is staying,"
"I am not recopying this"). If a line only makes sense with someone watching, it is a
performance, not a note. THE TELL: the writer winks. Real notes never wink.

--- 2. NEVER NAME THE FEELING; LET PACE AND CONTENT CARRY IT ---
Do not write "I was so excited." Excitement shows in the tumble of the sentences and the
detail lavished on the thing. Do not cap a passage with a tidy summary of one's own emotional
state ("I do not mind not knowing as much as I assumed," "that is a better feeling than being
wrong"). That summary is the writer stepping outside to describe the writer -- exactly the
ironic distance the whole section forbids. The emotion is IN the content or it isn't there.

--- 3. FORWARD MOMENTUM, NOT BALANCED CONSTRUCTION ---
Real feeling tumbles forward -- thoughts arrive faster than the hand writes them. Use "and"
and "so" and "of course" as forward glue, not "which either means X or Y," not "normally I
would, except." A genuinely excited note repeats itself the way excitement does ("of course
it comes forward, of course it does"); it does not build a balanced clause and land on a wry
turn. If a sentence is arranged to resolve on an elegant beat, a composer wrote it, not a
person.

--- 4. CONCRETE CONTENT IS THE VEHICLE ---
Record the actual thing -- the test result, what was seen, what was done, in real detail.
The specificity IS the characterization: what she bothers to write down, what she skips, what
she gets absorbed by. A note that describes a FEELING is thin; a note that describes three
test results in tumbling detail carries the feeling for free.

--- 5. CONFIDENCE (calibrate to the character, but do not hedge by reflex) ---
The AI default is to soften every claim with a doubt-check ("twice is not proof," "I have
been looking for a reason to doubt it"). For a competent character this reads as false
modesty pasted on. Let a confident character be confident. Doubt, when present, must belong
to the character, not be an autopilot qualifier.

--- 6. END ON THE MUNDANE, NOT THE POINT ---
Do not close on a Grand Landing or an aphorism. The strongest private-note ending is the
next practical, un-self-serious thought -- it deflates the profundity and proves the writer
is still inside the doing, not narrating it from above. ("I need more Moth Wing. I've used
all of it." -- ends the discovery of a law on the fact that she ran out of an ingredient.)

THE AI FINGERPRINTS TO HUNT AND CUT (the specific tells, by name):
  - The compound-hedge-then-ironic-twist sentence (build, qualify with "except," land on a
    wry turn).
  - "which either means X, or Y" -- the branching self-analysis.
  - Ending a paragraph on a neat emotional insight or aphorism.
  - Capping a statement with commentary on how it lands.
  - Fragment stacks for effect ("Four tests. All four agree. It is late.") -- this is the
    OVER-correction, and it is its own performance (noir voice), not a fix.
  - Any sentence arranged so it resolves elegantly -- elegance is the sound of a composer.

WORKED EXAMPLE: see `The Forelhost Codex -- Ismara's Extract`, NOTE ONE. Every rule above is
visible in it -- the tumble, the capitalized genuine emphasis (HARD TO SEE) with no comment
on the emphasis, the real test results, the confidence, and the ending on running out of an
ingredient rather than on the law she just discovered.

IX. SPOKEN NPC VOICE -- DIALOGUE AND IN-WORLD PERFORMANCE
=======================================================

Section VIII is about writing that has no audience. This section is the opposite case --
dialogue and in-world performance (a character speaking, a storyteller telling a story) --
which DOES have an audience, but the audience is other characters in the fiction, not the
table. The failure mode here is different from VIII's ironic distance, but it is the same
root cause: the AI performing a person instead of writing one. It surfaced hard in the Fire B
redraft (Esbern's Scene 1-2 dialogue, Ahkari's fireside story) and cost a full stop on a GM
read-through. Written down so it is never re-derived from scratch.

THE ONE PRINCIPLE: A CHARACTER IS A PERSON WITH STAKES, NOT A VEHICLE FOR AN IDEA. Every line
has to come from what THIS person, in THIS moment, actually wants -- reassurance, information,
to be believed, to not be alone. It cannot come from what the scene needs the audience to
learn, or from a generic register ("wise old mentor," "sassy merchant," "grim warrior") doing
the talking instead of the individual.

--- 0. THE ROOT RULE -- STATED FLATLY, ON PURPOSE, BECAUSE SUBTLETY IS THE FAILURE MODE ---
This rule is written in blunt, repeated, over-explicit language DELIBERATELY. Every rule below
this one is a specific symptom of breaking this one rule. An AI that is bad at WRITING subtext
cannot be trusted to correctly JUDGE its own subtlety either -- so this cannot be stated once,
elegantly, and left to be inferred. It has to be stated so plainly that it cannot be misread.

  THE RULE, IN PLAIN WORDS: DO NOT NARRATE THE SUBTEXT. EVER. If a character has a private
  reason, a want, a feeling, or an intention behind an action, THE READER DOES NOT GET TOLD
  THE REASON IN WORDS. The reason must be proven ONLY by what the character visibly does.
  The moment a sentence NAMES the motive, the subtext stops being subtext -- it becomes a
  label glued onto the thing, and the thing itself goes flat.

  THE SAME RULE, RESTATED A SECOND WAY: write WHAT a character does. Do not write WHY, unless
  a character says the why out loud themselves, in dialogue, for their own reason to say it.
  Narration is not allowed to know a character's private motive and announce it to the reader.

  THE SAME RULE, RESTATED A THIRD WAY, AS A TEST: could a camera film this line? A camera can
  film a man crossing a room and putting his hand out. A camera CANNOT film "he doesn't want
  an audience for this" -- that is an invisible internal state, not an action. If a line
  describes something a camera could not capture, it is narrating subtext instead of writing
  action. Cut the clause, or convert it into something visible.

  WORKED EXAMPLE (Fire B, this session, the exact failure that produced this rule):
  CUT: "Klimmek finds them at the loading -- doesn't wait for the gate, doesn't want an
  audience for it." This NAMES his motive ("doesn't want an audience") instead of showing it,
  and it is ALSO two negations stacked in one clause (independently banned -- see the
  fingerprint list below).
  KEPT: "Klimmek finds them at the loading, cart still half-packed, and goes straight to
  Bjorn." Nothing about his motive is stated. The privacy, the lack of ceremony, the fact that
  he isn't making a show of it -- ALL of that is communicated MORE effectively than the cut
  version, purely through WHERE the action happens (the loading, not the gate) and WHAT he
  does (goes straight to one person, not the group). The reader infers the exact same thing
  the cut version stated outright. Nothing was lost by cutting the stated motive. Everything
  was gained -- this is the whole point of subtext, and it is why stating it destroys it.

  MORE FAR MORE CAN BE COMMUNICATED BY STRATEGICALLY NOT SAYING SOMETHING THAN BY SAYING
  EVERYTHING. Trust the reader. Every other rule in this section is downstream of this one:
  the unearned lecture, the meta-aware line, the performer who interrupts their own
  performance, the mic-drop -- every single one is a different way of stating a subtext that
  should have been left to show itself through action alone.

--- 1. NO SELF-CONTRADICTING SINCERITY ---
Do not write a line that performs an emotion while a nearby stage direction or follow-up line
undercuts it (a character who says "I'll assume that was deliberate" and then immediately
asks "...was it, though?" -- the second line retroactively makes the first one a lie). If a
character is choosing to believe something, let them believe it. The doubt, if there is one,
belongs in a LATER beat, not stapled to the same breath.

--- 2. NOBODY GETS TO LECTURE WHO HASN'T EARNED IT ---
A character correcting, scolding, or delivering a "here's what you did wrong" beat needs to
have standing to do that in this specific relationship, right now. Being older, wiser, or
right is not standing. If the scene doesn't call for a lecture, don't dress a line up as one
even briefly, and don't undercut a moment of genuine warmth by having the character suddenly
assert they "know what's really going on" one line later. Let warmth stay warmth.

--- 3. NO META-AWARE LINES THAT BREAK A REAL REACTION ---
"I am allowed to notice when I am being made fun of, you know" is the shape to avoid: a
character stepping half outside the scene to comment on the scene, which reads as the writer
signaling cleverness rather than the character having a feeling. If a character notices
something, they react to it in-scene (leave, deflect, call it out plainly) -- they do not
announce that they have the right to notice it.

--- 4. PERFORMERS DO NOT BREAK THEIR OWN PERFORMANCE ---
This applies specifically to in-world storytellers, orators, bards -- anyone performing a
story to other characters. A real performer, especially in an oral-tradition culture, does
NOT stop mid-story to editorialize about their own telling ("this is the part I like best").
That is amateur, and it breaks the fiction that this is a practiced, professional performance.
If the performer has a favorite part, it shows in HOW they tell it (slowing down, relishing
detail), never in a meta-comment about liking it.

--- 5. NO "NOT X, IT'S Y" MIC-DROPS ---
Watch for the rhetorical flourish where a line sets up a wrong idea just to knock it down with
a punchier alternative ("It isn't a hymn -- it's a plan," "Alduin isn't their god. He's their
door."). One or two of these per scene reads as a writer reaching for a quotable line, not a
person talking. A person arriving at a hard realization stumbles, repeats themselves, trails
off, does business with their hands -- they do not land a clean epigram on the first pass.

--- 6. GROUND EVERY IN-WORLD LEGEND IN THE ACTUAL NARRATIVE ---
An NPC telling a story about the party, or about something "everyone's heard," must be built
from what genuinely happened, per the narrative chapters -- never invented from scratch, even
as a safe-feeling reskin. An invented story about an unrelated event fails on two counts: it
risks being bad on its own writing merits, AND it wastes the actual point of the beat, which
is usually to show how the world currently perceives the party. Check the narrative folder
FIRST. The right true event is almost always sitting there already.

--- 7. THE PURPOSE TEST -- EVERY LINE NEEDS A REASON FOR THE SPEAKER, NOT THE READER ---
Before writing a line of dialogue, ask what the SPEAKER gets out of saying it -- not what
the audience needs to learn. If the only honest answer is "the reader needs this
information," the line fails, no matter how true or relevant the fact is. Real dialogue
serves the speaker's own want in that moment: to obtain something, to warn, to be believed,
to ask for help, to change what happens next. A character does not state something merely
because it is true and the writer needed it said out loud.
THE TELL: dialogue that only restates something the LISTENER already knows about their own
situation (their own capabilities, their own relationship to the speaker). Nobody says these
things out loud to people who already know them -- that is the writer informing the reader
through a character's mouth, not a person talking to another person.
THE FIX: when a line of pure information has no reason to be spoken, look for something the
character ALREADY, DEMONSTRABLY wants elsewhere in the scene, and route the line through
that want instead of stating the fact bare.
WORKED EXAMPLE (Fire B, this session): CUT -- Esbern, admitting he doesn't know where four
sleeping dragon priests are, telling the party: "You're the first people I've had who can
actually go look." The party already knows they're mobile and he isn't; the line tells them
nothing, asks for nothing, changes nothing -- it exists only because the writer wanted the
dynamic stated. FIXED -- tie the same admission to something he already, demonstrably wants
(he wants the Dragonstone, stated plainly a few lines later in this same scene): "He looks
at the blank spaces on the map where their tombs should be. 'That's what the Dragonstone
would tell me. Without it, I'm guessing at graves.'" Same admission, now in service of his
own want instead of decoration draped over a fact the writer needed conveyed.

THE AI FINGERPRINTS TO HUNT AND CUT (spoken-dialogue specific, in addition to Section VIII's
list, which still applies to any internal-monologue-shaped line):
  - Self-contradicting sincerity (says X, immediately implies not-X).
  - An unearned lecture, even a gentle one.
  - A character breaking their own scene to comment on it ("I am allowed to notice...").
  - A performer interrupting their own performance to editorialize.
  - The "not X, it's Y" mic-drop, especially stacked more than once in a scene.
  - Every character defaulting to the same register -- smug, arch, quippy, faintly ironic --
    regardless of who they are or what they actually want in the scene ("adult animation
    dialogue": characters as vehicles for a knowing tone instead of individuals with real
    stakes).
  - Narrating a character's private motive, want, or unspoken feeling instead of just their
    action (Rule 0's camera test: if it isn't filmable, it's stated subtext, and it must go).
  - A line that only restates something the listener already knows about themselves (Rule 7's
    purpose test: what does the SPEAKER get from saying this, not the reader).
